    <segment id="1" parent="16" relname="span">Intuitiveness is a very important principle in interface design.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="1" relname="elaboration">
It is important for users to be able to easily use an interface without becoming frustrated.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="4" relname="concession">
Intuitive design is hard to measure </segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="14" relname="span">
but we could look at using quantitative/ performance based measuremnts that can look at how long users take to accomplish partiicular tasks.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="6" relname="purpose">
Also, we can collect feedback from users during tests of the interface</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="10" relname="span"> to see how well the interface flows and if there are any rough areas that could be re-worked.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="10" relname="elaboration">
User feedback is probably the best tool to assess how intuitive a interface is.</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="9" relname="background">
This is one common msitakes many interface designers make; </segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="12" relname="span">
not going back to see what users think about the design of the interface.</segment>
